ame in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is probably derived from the surname. In England this surname is found mainly in the West Midlands; it has also spread into Wales. In Ireland this form is common in Ulster; MacLysaght records that it was taken there from England in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Memory","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":4,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705187,"age":113,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mabel de Mowbray was born about 1102, in Cumberland, England. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Dacre."},"et":{"about 1102–":"umbes 1102–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1102–Female":"1102–Surnud","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1102":"umbes 1102","1180":"1180","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1102–":"noin 1102–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1102–Female":"1102–Kuollut","Abt 1130":"noin 1130","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1102":"noin 1102","1180":"1180","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"about 1102–":"environ 1102–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1130–1180":"1130–1180","1102–Female":"1102–Décédée","Abt 1130":"environ 1130","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1102":"1102","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1102":"environ 1102","1180":"1180","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mabel de Mowbray est née enviro